			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">To develop a compositional framework and a method for specifying and developing fault-tolerant programs and algorithms for fault-tolerance.Progress:This project is nearing its final stages and most of its objectives have been met and reported in the publications listed below. The last objective is to provide a formal framework for specifying and verifying the timing properties of fault-tolerant programs.  Z. Liu & M. Joseph,  Specification & verification of recovery in asynchronous communicating systems , in Formal Techniques in Real-time & Fault-tolerant Systems, Kluwer Academic Publishers, 1993, pp 137-166.D. Peled & M. Joseph,  A compositional approach to fault-tolerance using formula transformation LNCS 694, Springer-Verlag, 1993, pp 173-184.D. Peled & M. Joseph, A compositional framework for fault-tolerance by specification transformation , Th. Comp. Sc., Vol 128, pp 99-125.Z. Liu & M. Joseph,  Specifying & Verifying fault-tolerance by transformations , in Mathematics of Dependable Systems, Oxford University Press, 1995.Z. Liu, M. Joseph & T. Janowski,  Specifying schedulability for real-time programs , Formal Aspects of Computing (to appear).</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
